nhang stehend betrachtet.  aThe rejection of contaminating wind power by the Ikojts in Mexico makes it clear that the relationship between nature, renewable energy and social life can be thought differently.  afunded by Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHuave IndiansxSocial aspectszMexicozTehuantepec, Isthmus of. 0aHuave IndianszMexicozTehuantepec, Isthmus ofxAttitudes. 0aWind power plantsxSocial aspectszMexicozTehuantepec, Isthmus of. 4aEthnologie. 4aHuave. 4aIndigenität. 4aKontamination. 4aKultur. 4aKulturanthropologie. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLateinamerika. 4aMexiko. 4aNatur. 4aUmwelt. 4aUmweltsoziologie. 4aWindenergie. 4aWindkraft. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aContamination.  aCultural Anthropology.  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aEnvironment.  aEnvironmental Sociology.  aEthnology.  aHuave.  aIndigeneity.  aLatin America.  aMexico.  aNature.  aWind Energy.  aWind Power.1 aDürr, Eveline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aLudwig-Maximilians-Universität Münchenefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.14361/9783839448151zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839448151423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783839448151.jpg  a978-3-11-069629-5  DG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_PPALL 